## Radius & shape tokens

Corner radii come from a concentric **8 / 6 / 4** scale, capped at 8px. **Never
hardcode a radius** — always use the token, so nested corners stay smaller than
their container:

- `--radius-lg` (8px) — card / large containers (`.hero`, `.panel`).
- `--radius-md` (6px) — sub-cards, inner panels, avatar/badge squircles
  (`.avatar-mark`, `.badge-medallion`, `.member-avatar`).
- `--radius-sm` (4px) — buttons, chips, tabs (`.tab`), inputs, focus rings.

Only non-token exceptions allowed: full pills (`999px`) and circles (`50%`)
where that shape is intended, and thin data-viz bars (`.chart-bar`, 2px).
Nothing may exceed 8px. New components must follow this mapping.

## Button icon sizing standard (`.btn svg`)

Every icon inside a `.btn` (any variant/size, any viewport) is sized once,
globally, by `.btn svg:not([width]) { width: 1em; height: 1em; flex-shrink: 0 }`
in `index.css` — **never** size a button's icon with a one-off wrapper class or
inline style.

- **Why this exists:** Phosphor's `IconBase` omits the SVG `width`/`height`
  attributes entirely when an icon gets neither an explicit `size` prop nor a
  context size (`main.tsx`'s `IconContext` only sets `weight`, not `size`). An
  `<svg>` left with no intrinsic size falls back to the browser's oversized
  default object box, inflating the whole button around it — this is exactly
  what broke the Rule Chips "Add Rule" button when its `CaretDown` icon
  shipped with no `size` prop and no CSS constraining it.
- **`1em`, not a fixed px:** scales the icon with the button's own font-size,
  so `.btn--small` automatically gets a proportionally smaller icon than the
  base `.btn` — consistent across every button size without a breakpoint rule
  (buttons don't change font-size by viewport, so this is viewport-consistent
  for free). Matches the "size relative to adjacent text" icon guidance in
  `design-system.md`.
- **The `:not([width])` guard is load-bearing.** Icons that pass an explicit
  `size` prop (e.g. `size={16}` in `StrategyActions`) already render a
  `width` attribute — the guard excludes them so this rule can't silently
  resize an already-correct icon. Don't drop it "for simplicity."
- **New icon-only buttons** (`.icon-btn`, `.forge-table-close`, etc.) already
  have their own dedicated `svg` sizing rules — this standard is specifically
  for icons inside **text** buttons (`.btn` + a label). Give a new icon-only
  button family its own explicit `svg` rule instead of relying on this one.

## Conviction chip breakdown standard (`.watch-summary-chips`)

The Watch summary (`WatchSummary` in `WatchlistWidget.tsx`) is used by Home
**Current Watch** (`readOnly`) and Forge **Watch Preview**
(`readOnly` + `previewStrategyId`). Preview renames the panel, hides edit/create,
limits the source switcher to that strategy's `appliedPortfolioIds`, and shows an
empty state when none are applied — multi-strategy conviction on tickers is
unchanged.

**Empty-source guide** (blank portfolio / watchlist only): stock `ForgeToast`
(`tone="info"`, dismiss stays until closed; `sessionStorage` per source id).
Portfolio copy = paper book + forge/apply/edit steps; watchlist copy = track
without size yet. Do not invent a parallel empty-state banner.

**Editable cash** (portfolio sources only, edit mode): totals footer Cash becomes
a compact `.watch-cash-input` (same compact figure patterns as qty — `font:
inherit`, tokens only). Draft participates in dirty/Cancel/Update like qty;
`updatePortfolioCash` persists + appends a `cash` ledger transaction. Read mode /
watchlists / Watch Preview: display-only Cash unchanged.

Per ticker it shows **one block per assigned strategy** (default
strategies via `holdings[].strategyIds`; custom copies via applied portfolio —
`AppState.getAppliedStrategiesForTicker` / `strategiesForTicker`), each with its
own rule-chip breakdown:

- **The strategy-name chip stack (`.signal-stack`) and the breakdown blocks
  below MUST come from the same source.** Both are built from the same
  `strategyBreakdowns` array (`{ strategy, alignment }[]`) computed once in
  `WatchlistWidget`. For seeded defaults, `holding.strategyIds` is the
  per-ticker assignment (NVDA → Aggressive only, CRM → VGD only) even when both
  strategies list the same `appliedPortfolioIds`. Never show every
  portfolio-applied strategy on every ticker.
- Each strategy's own chip result set comes from
  `AppState.getStrategyChipBreakdown(strategyId, ticker, portfolioId)` — a
  fresh, informational `scoreStock` call **independent of buckets**, not the
  bucket-scoped headline alignment. `weightPct`/`holdingDays` are intentionally
  left unset (no single canonical value across arbitrary applied strategies),
  so Position Size / Hold Timeframe chips read "no data" here — this doesn't
  touch the real, bucket-driven conviction number shown above it.
- **"Calculating Conviction"** — every `ChipResult` with `outcome !== "no-data"`
  (pass or fail; both mean the chip had real data and counted).
- **"Excluded (No Data)"** — every `ChipResult` with `outcome === "no-data"`.
- Both groups reuse `.forge-box-body` (the Configure card's chip-box look) and
  plain `.forge-pill` chips — excluded chips get `.forge-pill--off` (the same
  45%-opacity dimming used for a manually-disabled chip everywhere else), so
  "no data" reads identically to "user-disabled" without inventing a new
  visual state. **Don't add a third color/state for "no data" specifically**
  — it already shares the disabled-chip look on purpose (a `null` metric is
  scored "no data," already treated the same as `enabled: false`, i.e.
  excluded — the styling should match that).

## Forge rule chip Time column

`RuleChipsTableModal` / `Layer3ZoneTableModal` label the former "Date Range"
column **Time**. For timeframed technical metrics (`METRICS[key].timeframed`),
options are candle sizes (15m–1M); fundamentals keep fiscal labels. New chips
default Time from strategy `technicalsInterval` via `resolveChipTime` — do not
invent a parallel timeframe picker. Data Point dropdowns may use `<optgroup>`
from `MetricMeta.group` (MACD, Stochastic, etc.).

## Forge Risk / Trade / Layer 3 metric lenses

Risk Rule Chips, Trade Management Rule Chips, and Layer 3 zone chip tables use
**`ForgeSectionTabs`** (`.forge-section-tabs` / `.forge-section-tab`) with three
lenses: **Thesis · Technical · Market** — same strip as Configure section tabs,
not page-level / auth **`Tabs`** (`.tabs` / `.tab`). Do not restyle Home/auth
`Tabs`. Layout chrome: `.forge-metric-lens` / `.forge-metric-lens-hint`.
`chip.category` stays the host category (scoring impact: none). Data Point
options come from `metricsForLens`; row visibility from `lensForMetric`.

**Stable shell while switching lenses (desktop + tablet):** pass
`stableTabs` + `stableTabsTableMin` on `ForgeTableModal`
(`.forge-table-modal--stable-tabs`). At `≥ 768px` the card height is
`min(chrome + tallest-lens table min, 90vh)` so tabs and footer don’t jump
when switching Thesis / Technical / Market. Mobile (`< 768px`) is already a
full-screen sheet — leave it alone. Same breakpoint as Onboarding’s
fixed-height modal.

## Forge table Actions column standard (`.forge-table-row` / `.forge-table--tags`)

Both Forge table modals (`RuleChipsTableModal`'s rows, `TagsTableModal`'s
rows — shared across **every** category: Thesis, Setup, Risk, Position, Trade,
Timeframe) size their rightmost **Actions** column as a **fixed pixel width**
in `.forge-table-row`'s `grid-template-columns` (not `fr`/`minmax`, since it
holds a stable icon count, not flexible text). A fixed grid track **never
grows to fit overflowing content** — if the icon row inside needs more space
than the track provides, it silently overflows *backward* into the previous
(Rule Weight / Tag Weight) column instead of wrapping or clipping, which is
exactly what happened when a third icon (`BookmarkSimple`, "Save to My
Chips") was added to Rule Chips rows without widening their `82px` track.

- **Before adding a new action icon to a table row, widen its Actions
  track first**: `icon count × 28px (.icon-btn) + (icon count − 1) × 6px gap`,
  then add real breathing room (don't size it exactly to content — both
  tracks are `108px` today, sized for 3 icons with a few px of slack; a razor-
  thin margin risks overflow at different zoom levels/font sizes).
- **This is shared, not per-category** — both `.forge-table-row` (chips) and
  `.forge-table--tags .forge-table-row` (tags) are used for every category via
  the same two modal components, so fixing the column width once fixes it
  everywhere; there's no per-category CSS to hunt down.
- Mobile (`≤ 767px`) reflows rows into stacked cards
  (`grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr)`) and switches Actions to
  `justify-content: flex-start`, so this overflow risk is desktop/tablet-grid
  specific — verify any icon-count change at the grid breakpoint, not just
  mobile.

## Modal view-state standard (no modal-in-a-modal)

When a modal needs a secondary view (e.g. a picker, a sub-form) that isn't
simply "more fields in the same view," swap it in as a **mutually exclusive
sibling view of the same modal card** — never render it as a bordered/boxed
panel nested *alongside* the modal's normal content (that reads as a modal
inside a modal).

- **Shared chrome stays put.** The modal's own head (title + close `X`,
  `.forge-table-close`) is rendered once, outside the view conditional, and
  stays visible in every view — it's the only way to fully close the modal
  regardless of which view is active.
- **Exactly one view renders its body content at a time**, gated by a single
  piece of state (e.g. `pickerOpen`). Each view's own root element is
  `flex: 1 1 auto; min-height: 0; overflow-y: auto` (matches `.forge-table`) so
  it fills the same body region and scrolls the same way, whichever view is
  showing.
- **A secondary view is flush, not boxed.** It gets no extra
  border/background/margin of its own (that's the "nested panel" smell) — it
  should look like a first-class replacement for the table body, not an inset
  card floating inside one. Give it its own small head row (a `.breadcrumb`
  back link + a view title) if it needs one, styled to match the modal's own
  head rhythm, not a separate mini-modal look. The back affordance is the
  shared **`.breadcrumb`** component (matching every other breadcrumb
  app-wide — e.g. "My Strategies" on the Forge detail page) sitting left of
  the title, labeled with the view it returns to — **not** a `.forge-table-
  close`-styled icon button (that's reserved for actually closing the whole
  modal, in the modal's own top-level head).
- **Current adopter:** `RuleChipsTableModal`'s "Add Rule" picker
  (`.forge-chip-picker`) replaces `.forge-table-intro` +
  `.forge-table` + `.forge-table-actions` entirely while open, rather than
  inserting itself between them.

## Collapsible mobile row standard (`useIsMobile` / `.forge-row-summary`)

Mobile (`< 768px`) rows in both Forge table modals (`RuleChipsTableModal`,
`TagsTableModal` — every category) are **collapsed by default** to a compact
one-line summary, matching the "Add Rule" picker's `.chip-search-option` look
exactly, with a chevron that rotates to indicate state:

- **Mobile detection is JS, not CSS.** This is a genuinely different markup
  tree per state (a one-line summary vs. every field cell), not something
  `display: none` can switch — use the shared `useIsMobile()` hook
  (`src/lib/useIsMobile.ts`). Desktop/tablet always render every field cell
  regardless of any collapse state; the state only has an effect when
  `isMobile` is true.
- **Collapsed** — a `<button className="chip-search-option forge-row-summary">`
  reusing the picker's exact classes (`chip-search-option-label` +
  `chip-search-option-desc` for the two summary fields) plus a right-aligned
  `CaretDown` (`.forge-row-caret`, `margin-left: auto`). Tapping the whole row
  expands it — the entire card is the tap target, not a small icon.
- **Expanded** — the same summary button re-renders as the row's own header
  (`.forge-row-summary.is-expanded`, caret rotated via `.forge-row-caret--up`)
  followed by the row's normal full field cells, completely unchanged from the
  desktop/tablet markup. Tapping the header collapses back — it's a
  **persistent, separate control** from the fields below, so it never
  conflicts with editing an input/select inside the expanded row.
- **State:** a per-modal `Set<string>` of expanded row ids
  (`expandedRowIds`/`toggleRowExpanded`), starting empty (all collapsed).
  Don't persist this across renders of a *different* strategy/category — each
  modal mount starts fresh, matching how `draft` itself resets per mount.
- **Current adopters:** both Forge table modals, all 6 categories (shared
  components, so one implementation covers every category automatically).
  A future collapsible-row list should follow the same shape: reuse
  `.chip-search-option`'s classes for the summary rather than inventing new
  label/description styling.

## Cancel / Save-Update pair standard (`.forge-cancel-btn`)

Any **Cancel next to a primary commit action** (Update / Save / Add) — e.g. a
modal or inline-form footer — reuses the **same two button styles** every
time. Before adding a new Cancel/commit pair anywhere, check this rule first
instead of hand-rolling a plain `.btn--link`/`.btn--ghost` Cancel:

- **Cancel** = `.btn.btn--small.btn--link.forge-cancel-btn` + a leading bold
  `X` icon (`<X aria-hidden weight="bold" /> Cancel`) — gold/warning-toned
  text button, no fill.
- **Commit** = `.btn.btn--small.btn--solid` + a leading regular-weight icon
  matching the action (`Plus` for Add/Save, `FloppyDisk` for a dedicated Save
  action, etc.).
- **Current adopters:** `RuleChipsTableModal` (table Cancel/Update **and** the
  My Chips inline edit form's Cancel/Save Chip), `TagsTableModal`. Any new
  Cancel/commit pair — including ones nested inside a picker or inline form,
  not just a top-level modal footer — joins this list instead of forking a new
  style.
- `CaptainLogWidget`'s inline-form Cancel (`.btn--ghost`, no icon) predates
  this standard and is a narrower, non-modal context — don't treat it as a
  second valid pattern; new Cancel/commit pairs use `.forge-cancel-btn`.

## Selectable card interaction standard (`.select-card` / `.is-selected`)

Every card the user can **pick** — watchlist names (`.watch-item`), strategy
cards (`.strategy-card`), market-flow steps (`.flow-step` once selectable), and
any future selectable card — **must share one** rest / hover / selected
treatment. It lives once in the **"Selectable card interaction standard"** block
in `index.css`. Layout, padding, and content stay per-component; only the
interaction *surface* is shared, so the whole set looks and behaves identically.

| State | Treatment |
|-------|-----------|
| Rest | `1px solid var(--border-soft)` on `var(--surface-2)`, `--radius-md` |
| Hover | border → `var(--border-strong)`, `transform: translateY(-1px)` |
| Selected | gold border `rgb(241 178 74 / 0.55)`, `background: var(--surface-1)`, `box-shadow: var(--shadow-glow)` |
| Focus | global `:focus-visible` gold ring (2px `--accent-strong`) — never re-styled per card |

Rules:

- **Apply, don't reinvent.** Put `.select-card` on the interactive element (the
  card itself, or the wrapper that owns the border) and toggle `.is-selected`
  when chosen. The component keeps only its own layout/typography classes.
- **Mirror the state for a11y.** Reflect selection with `aria-pressed` (single-
  select toggles like the watchlist/strategy lists) or `aria-current` (nav).
- **Never hand-roll** `:hover` / active border + glow on a new selectable card,
  and never fork the values — change them in the shared block so every adopter
  moves together.
- **Current adopters:** `.watch-item`, `.strategy-card`, and `.flow-step` (the
  market-flow / weather cards — the li owns `.select-card` + the border/art; a
  full-card `.weather-hit` button absolutely fills the card and handles the click
  + `aria-pressed`, so the **whole card** opens the detail view. The content
  overlay is click-through (`pointer-events: none`) except the on-card selectors
  — the Sector/Industry typeahead (`.weather-select`, a `SearchableSelect`
  `on-graphics`) and the Stock `.weather-prevnext` toggle — which re-enable
  pointer events above the hit target so changing a layer doesn't navigate).

## Select / dropdown standard (`select.input` + `SearchableSelect`)

**Short catalogs** use a native `<select>` via **`Dropdown`**
(`src/components/Dropdown.tsx`) — `select.input` styling in `index.css`. Don't
re-inline `<label>` + `<select>`.

**Long catalogs** (GICS Sector / Industry) use **`SearchableSelect`**
(`src/components/SearchableSelect.tsx`): closed trigger matches `input` (+
optional `input--on-graphics`) with a CaretDown; expanded panel is a portaled
typeahead (`.chip-search-field` + `.multiselect-menu` / `.multiselect-option`)
matching Current Watch ticker suggestions — portaled so Weather card
`overflow: hidden` cannot clip it. Do not invent a third pick-one menu look.

- **`Dropdown`:** short lists where native picker UX is enough (portfolio
  switcher, Strategy Assignment, Create Ship privacy). Never hand-roll a
  parallel native select. `DropdownOption` supports optional `disabled`
  (renders a greyed non-selectable `<option>`, e.g. 15m "Future Capability")
  and `group` (consecutive same-`group` options wrap in a native `<optgroup>`,
  e.g. the Forge cadence "Intraday — session close" / "Candle close" clusters).
- **`SearchableSelect`:** long searchable single-select. Trigger variants:
  `default` (surface) and `on-graphics` (Weather art only — dark translucent
  fill). Reuse existing menu/option classes; don't fork row hover/radius.
- **Width:** wrap in a flex container (e.g. `.portfolio-switcher`,
  `.weather-select`) rather than overriding field width.
- **Label it.** Both components take a meaningful `label` (visually hidden).
- **Current `Dropdown` adopters:** portfolio/watchlist switcher, Strategy
  Assignment (`#assign-select`), Create Ship privacy, Forge Strategy Cadence
  (Strategy Check + Technicals, grouped + disabled 15m).
- **Current `SearchableSelect` adopters:** Market Weather Sector + Industry
  (`on-graphics`).

> A **step-through next/previous** control (e.g. the Market Weather Stock
> card's `.weather-prevnext`) is a distinct two-button toggle — appropriate
> when cycling a short ordered set in place without opening a menu. Two
> traversal modes: **wraparound** (Market Weather — never disabled) and
> **bounded** (Onboarding modal — ends `disabled`, styled by the shared
> `.weather-prevnext-btn:disabled` state; don't fork a new disabled look).

## Action menu standard (`ActionMenu`)

A button that reveals a short list of **one-shot actions** (as opposed to a
`Dropdown`/`MultiSelect`, which pick a *value*) is an `ActionMenu`
(`src/components/ActionMenu.tsx`) — never a hand-rolled button + conditional
`<ul>`. It renders exactly the trigger you give it (so the caller keeps full
control of the button's look, e.g. `.btn.btn--small`) and manages open state,
outside-click, and Escape itself, mirroring `MultiSelect`'s mechanics
(`.action-menu` relative wrapper + `.action-menu-list` absolute menu) but
right-aligned (`right: 0`) since triggers like "Add Rule" typically sit near a
panel's right edge — check which alignment fits before reusing the class
wholesale if a future trigger sits elsewhere.

- **Current adopter:** the Rule Chips table modal's "Add Rule" split button
  (`CaretDown` icon — swapped in for the old `Plus` icon specifically to signal
  "opens a menu" rather than "adds immediately") — items: "Add new blank
  chip" / "Select chip from system defaults or custom chips".
- Items are one-shot (`onSelect` fires and the menu closes) — for a
  pick-and-keep-open pattern, that's a different component; don't force it
  through `ActionMenu`.

## Chip search list standard (`ChipSearchList`)

A **searchable, metric-grouped, single-select chip list** — used by the Rule
Chips table modal's "Add Rule" picker (System Defaults / My Chips columns) —
is a distinct pattern from both `Dropdown` (native `<select>`, no search) and
`MultiSelect` (a compact, collapsible field trigger). `ChipSearchList`
(`src/components/ChipSearchList.tsx`) is **always inline-expanded** (no
open/closed trigger state of its own) because it lives inside an
already-expanded picker panel, not a compact form field:

- A search input (reusing `.input`, with a leading `MagnifyingGlass` icon)
  filters every group's options by chip label, description, and `meta` text.
- Options are grouped by **underlying data point** (metric label as the group
  heading, in the same order as the Data Point dropdown —
  `metricsForCategory`), not by source strategy — the same metric tested with
  different values/labels (e.g. a "Revenue Growth" chip in one default
  strategy vs. a "Hyper Growth" chip in another) surfaces under one heading so
  it's easy to compare.
- An optional `meta` tag per option (e.g. the source strategy name for a
  System Defaults option) and an optional `renderExtra` slot (e.g. My Chips'
  edit/delete icon buttons) — reuse these instead of forking the list markup.
- Reuses `MultiSelect`'s menu/option visual conventions (`.chip-search-list`
  mirrors `.multiselect-menu`; hover surface, `--radius-sm` rows) so it reads
  as part of the same design language despite being a new component.

See `data-architecture.md` ("Chip library") for what selecting a System
Defaults vs. My Chips option actually does to the data (copy vs.
copy-with-library-link) — that's a data-flow contract, not a styling one.

## Tooltip standard (`Tooltip.tsx` / `InfoTip`)

There is **one** tooltip affordance app-wide: the dark rounded popover
(`.tooltip`) rendered by the shared `Tooltip` component (`InfoTip` is its
info-icon trigger, used beside Configure-card section labels). Always reach
for `Tooltip`/`InfoTip` for hover/tap explanatory content — never hand-roll a
one-off popover.

- **Desktop/tablet (`≥ 768px`)** — reveals on hover / focus (React `open`
  state). Portaled to `document.body` using stock `.tooltip` / `.tooltip--wide`
  only; layout is `position: fixed` via inline styles (no new `.tooltip*` CSS)
  so card / panel `overflow: hidden` cannot clip it. `pointer-events: none`
  (decorative, dismisses on mouse-out/blur). No close button on desktop.
  After reveal, clamps into the viewport (prefer below; flip above when there
  is room; otherwise pin). Do not invent a second tooltip component or novel
  tooltip CSS for edge placement.
- **Mobile (`< 768px`)** — touch has no hover, so behavior switches to
  **tap-to-toggle**: tapping the trigger sets `.tooltip-wrap.is-open`, and the
  tooltip renders as a **sheet fixed to the bottom-center of the viewport**
  via `.tooltip--viewport-sheet` (`position: fixed; left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%)`) — **not** anchored to the trigger. The sheet is
  **portaled to `document.body`** so sticky header `backdrop-filter` cannot
  trap fixed positioning (TopNav Demo chip). Forge rule chips / tags use this
  same bottom-center sheet — **do not** change that pin or invent a different
  mobile placement for Forge. `pointer-events` flips to `auto` and a white
  Phosphor **`X`** close button (`.tooltip-close`, bold weight) dismisses it.
  The mobile CSS block in `index.css`, keyed off `@media (max-width: 767px)`,
  is the single source of truth for sheet styling.
- **Dismissal (mobile):** the open tooltip closes on **any tap outside its own
  wrap** — a single `pointerdown` listener on `document` (added only while
  `open`, comparing `event.target` against a ref on `.tooltip-wrap`) drives
  this. Don't reach for a backdrop or per-navigation callback instead — the
  outside-tap listener already covers every dismiss case for free, because
  each one begins with a tap somewhere outside this tooltip:
  - **Genuine outside tap** — the explicit case.
  - **Switching tabs/sections that toggle via CSS** (e.g. the Configure card's
    section tabs) rather than unmounting — the tab button tap is "outside".
  - **Navigating to a different app page** — the nav tap is "outside", and
    since `ActivePage` in `App.tsx` conditionally renders (not CSS-hides) each
    page, the old page's component tree — Tooltip included — actually
    unmounts too, resetting `open` for free as a second line of defense.
  - A new dismiss scenario should still route through "tap somewhere closes
    the currently-open tooltip" rather than adding a bespoke callback.
- **Clearing sticky bottom toolbars:** the mobile sheet's `bottom` offset uses
  `max()` against `--sticky-footer-h` (see "Live chrome dimension variables"
  above) so it always sits 4px above a mounted `ActionFooter` (e.g. the
  Configure card's action row) instead of overlapping it, falling back to the
  plain safe-area baseline when no such footer is mounted. Any new
  viewport-fixed mobile element that could collide with a sticky footer should
  clear it the same way, not with a hardcoded offset.
- **Adding a new tooltip trigger:** wrap it in `<Tooltip>` (or use `<InfoTip>`
  for the info-icon case) — don't add new hover/tap-reveal CSS per instance.

## Status chip coloring (`.chip.status--*`)

There is **one** chip color set, defined once in `index.css`: `.status--positive`
(green), `.status--warning` (amber), `.status--negative` (red), `.status--neutral`
(info blue). Each pairs a solid text color with a 16%-alpha tint of the same hue.
These exactly match the Figma chip styles — never hardcode chip colors; apply a
`status--*` class.

A chip's color is driven by **what the chip means**, and there are two distinct
rules in play (don't conflate them):

- **Categorical / tone chips** (condition, signal, status) color by their own
  semantic tone — e.g. the weather `ConditionChip` maps condition severity →
  tone via `SEVERITY_TONE`. A positive condition is always green regardless of
  any number.
- **Measure / range chips** color by **where a value lands in a range**, not by
  the surrounding item's tone. Use a small `*Tone(value)` helper with named
  thresholds (e.g. `confidenceTone` in `lib/weather` when a confidence % is
  shown elsewhere): `>= 70` positive, `40–69` warning, `< 40` negative. A new
  "how good is this number" chip (score, fill %, etc.) follows this band
  pattern — never reuse the parent's tone. Market Weather layer cards show
  condition only (no confidence chip).

When adding a chip, decide which rule applies first, then reuse the matching
helper (or add a small `*Tone(value)` helper next to its data) so the mapping is
defined once and stays consistent.

**Chips inside a `<button>`:** a bare `<button>` resets `font-family` to the UA
default (Arial) and `line-height` to `normal`. Because `.chip` height comes from
the inherited `1.55` line-height, a chip in an un-reset button renders in Arial
**and** ~6px shorter than the same chip in body context. Any button wrapping
text/chips MUST set `font: inherit` (as `.btn`, `.flow-select`, `.weather-headpill`
do). This is the standard fix for "the font looks like Arial" / "this chip is
shorter than the others".

This same "color = meaning" rule applies to `.forge-pill` (the Forge rule-chip/
tag pill, a separate visual family from `.chip` — smaller, blue by default via
`--forge-chip-text`/`--forge-chip-surface`). `.forge-pill--applied` (the
Configure card's "Tickers In Applied Portfolios" box) reuses the exact
`.status--positive` green token rather than a one-off color, since it's
conceptually the same "positive/included" meaning — green there means "this
ticker is covered," not a value judgment about the ticker itself. Any new
`.forge-pill` variant should resolve its color from an existing token this way
before adding a new one.

## App shell (`.app` / `.app-main` / `SiteFooter`)

The shell is `AppShell` → `TopNav` + `.app-main` (the active page) + `SiteFooter`.
It wraps **every authenticated page**, so the header and footer are single shared
instances — never add a page-local header or footer. The scroll model differs by
viewport on purpose:

- **Desktop / tablet (`≥ 768px`)** — `.app` is a fixed-height (`100dvh`) flex
  column with `overflow: hidden`; `.app-main` is the **single scrolling region**
  (`overflow: hidden auto`, `overscroll-behavior-y: contain`). The header and
  footer are pinned chrome (always visible) and the content scrolls between them.
  The **document must never scroll** here (no second scrollbar dragging the
  header/footer): the root is locked to the viewport via
  `@media (min-width: 768px) { html:has(.app), body:has(.app), #root:has(.app) { height: 100%; overflow: hidden } }`.
  Don't put `min-height: 100vh`/`100dvh` on `body` or on a page root — it fights
  `.app`'s `100dvh` and reintroduces the outer scrollbar.
- **Mobile (`≤ 767px`)** — the **whole page scrolls** on every page: `.app` is
  `height: auto; min-height: 100svh; overflow: visible` and `.app-main` is
  `flex: 1 1 auto; overflow: visible`. The header stays sticky at top; the footer
  is end-of-page content that flows **below** the content (scroll to reveal)
  instead of stealing viewport height. Don't reintroduce a fixed shell on mobile.
- Home layers its deck on top of the mobile model (`.app-main:has(.home-page)` is
  content-height + flush tabs); other pages get the standard model for free.
- Applies to the authenticated shell only — never to the login/onboarding screens
  (they render outside `AppShell` and have no footer by design).

### `SiteFooter` (`src/components/SiteFooter.tsx`)

The one and only footer. Rendered once by `AppShell`, so it appears identically on
every page (and any future page that renders in the shell). Content is locked.
Its responsive behavior is the `.site-footer` rule described above — pinned on
desktop/tablet, flowing end-of-page on mobile. Keep all footer changes in this
component + `.site-footer`; never add a second footer.

### Live chrome dimension variables (`--app-header-h` / `--sticky-footer-h`)

Two CSS custom properties report the live pixel height of pinned shell chrome
so other viewport-fixed UI can offset/clear it instead of hardcoding a magic
number — set via `useLayoutEffect` + `ResizeObserver` (so they track resize,
content reflow, and safe-area changes), consumed with a pixel fallback
(`var(--x, 96px)`) so nothing breaks before the effect runs.

- **`--app-header-h`** — the site header's height, set on `document.documentElement`
  by `AppShell`. Consumers: the mobile home section-tabs sticky offset, the
  mobile Forge list-view dock sizing.
- **`--sticky-footer-h`** — the currently-mounted `ActionFooter`'s own rendered
  height (its safe-area padding is already baked in — don't add
  `env(safe-area-inset-bottom)` again on top of it), set by `ActionFooter`
  itself and removed on unmount. Consumer: the mobile `Tooltip` sheet clears it
  by 4px (see "Tooltip standard" below).
- **Assumption:** at most one height-reporting instance of a given kind is
  mounted at a time (true today — one header; the Forge dock and Configure
  card footer are mutually exclusive on mobile). If a page ever needs two
  simultaneous `ActionFooter`s, `--sticky-footer-h` needs to become
  per-instance (e.g. scoped to a container, not `documentElement`) — don't
  silently let a second instance clobber the first.
- **Adding a new one:** follow this exact pattern (measure in a
  `useLayoutEffect`, `ResizeObserver` + `resize` listener, clean up on
  unmount) rather than a one-off `getBoundingClientRect()` snapshot, so it
  stays correct across content/orientation changes.

## Pages — layout & scroll contract (applies to every new page)

A "page" is the component rendered into `.app-main` (see `App.tsx` →
`ActivePage`). New pages inherit the shell's scroll model for free, so they must
**not** fight it:

- **The page is just content.** Render a single root element (convention:
  `<div className="page <name>-page">`) that sizes to its content. Let the shell
  own scrolling — `.app-main` scrolls on desktop/tablet, the page scrolls on
  mobile. A new page needs **no** special height/overflow CSS to scroll.
- **Never create a second scroller for the whole page.** Don't put `100vh` /
  `100dvh` / `min-height: 100vh` or `overflow: auto/scroll` on a page root or a
  full-page wrapper. That produces the double-scrollbar bug (document + main).
  The only viewport-height owner is `.app`.
- **Bounded internal scroll is allowed for a region, not the page.** If a region
  inside a card must scroll independently (long list, log, etc.), scroll that
  inner region with the **Card scroll standard** below (8px bar, 4px insets) —
  don't make the page scroll to accommodate it.
- **Cards/panels** on a page use the shared `.panel`/`.hero` contract: 16px
  padding, radius tokens, and the card-scroll standard when they scroll. Reuse
  existing widgets; don't restyle them per page.
- **No page-local header or footer** — those come from `AppShell`.
- **Top spacing** is owned by the shell's `--page-gap` (see design-system "Page
  top spacing rule"); don't add ad-hoc top margins to push content off the
  header.

If a new page seems to *need* its own page-level scroll or a viewport height,
that's a signal to revisit this contract rather than override it — flag it.

## Header responsive behavior

The header (`.site-header`) is `position: sticky; top: 0` on every viewport.
`.site-header-inner` is a CSS grid with two layouts:

- **Default (mobile + tablet, `< 1200px`)** — two rows:
  `"brand account"` / `"nav nav"`. Nav is left-aligned on its own row.
- **Desktop single bar (`≥ 1200px`)** —
  `grid-template-columns: minmax(max-content, 1fr) auto minmax(max-content, 1fr)`,
  areas `"brand nav account"`. The `max-content` side tracks reserve the
  brand's/account's real width so the centered nav **slides right rather than
  overlapping the wordmark**, and the bar falls back to the two-row layout once
  the single row can no longer fit. If you change brand/nav width, re-verify
  this `1200px` threshold (it's tuned, not arbitrary).

UX intent: nav stays visually centered while there is room, degrades
gracefully (shift, then stack) — it must never collide or clip.

## Home cards — scroll behavior per viewport

The deck is `.home-grid` → `.home-grid__track` → three `.home-slide`s
(`--helm` / `--market` / `--watch`). Scrolling differs by viewport **on
purpose**; keep these distinctions:

- **Desktop (`≥ 1024px`)** — full-height dashboard. Three columns on one row
  (Watch 1–3 · Helm 4–9 · Market 10–12). Each card fills the viewport height
  and shrinks with it. The **page never scrolls**; instead a card's own content
  scrolls *inside* it only when the viewport is too short. The card (`.hero` /
  `.panel`) is a fixed-height shell with `overflow: hidden`; an **inner region**
  scrolls (`.hero-body`, `.flow-steps`, `.watchlist-items`) via `overflow:
  hidden auto` + `scrollbar-gutter: stable`. Helm keeps `.panel-head` fixed and
  scrolls `.hero-body`; other panels keep head/intro/form fixed and scroll
  only the list.

### Card padding & scrollbar placement (matches Figma)

Applies to **every card app-wide** (`.panel` and `.hero`), not just the home
deck.

- **16px padding on all sides** of every card, all viewports, so content
  breathes — baked into the base `.panel` rule (`padding: 1rem`) and `.hero`.
  Don't re-set card padding per page/breakpoint.
- When a region scrolls **inside** a card, it gets the **card scroll standard**:
  an **8px bar parked 4px from the card edge with 4px between the bar and
  content** (4 + 8 + 4 = the 16px right inset). This is a **desktop effect**
  (the breakpoint where the region actually scrolls); mobile/tablet decks scroll
  at the page level, not inside cards.
  - Appearance (the 8px rounded bar) is shared once in the **"Card scroll
    standard"** block in `index.css` — grouped over `.hero-body`, `.flow-steps`,
    `.watchlist-items`, `.strategy-list`. Firefox uses `scrollbar-width: thin`.
  - Positioning is per-region at the breakpoint where it scrolls:
    `overflow: hidden auto; margin-right: -12px; padding-right: 4px;
    scrollbar-gutter: stable;`. The negative margin pulls the scroll box into
    the card's 16px padding so the bar lands 4px from the edge; `padding-right`
    re-opens the 4px gap to content; `scrollbar-gutter` keeps it stable.
  - **Never put the scroll on the padded card itself** (the bar would sit far
    inside the padding) — always scroll an inner region with this inset.
- **Adding a new scrollable card region:** add its selector to the "Card scroll
  standard" group (for the 8px bar) and give it the inset above in the
  breakpoint where it scrolls. Keep the card's own padding at 16px.
- **Tablet (`768–1199px`)** — Helm full-width top row; Market + Watch
  side-by-side below. Cards are **content-height and never scroll internally**;
  the page (`.app-main`) scrolls vertically.
- **Mobile (`< 768px`)** — Embla horizontal **swipe deck** (one card per
  screen), driven by the sticky `.home-tabs-shell` tabs. Cards are
  content-height and **must not scroll internally**; the deck (`.home-grid`)
  owns vertical scroll while `.app-main` is locked (`overflow: hidden`). Embla
  owns horizontal swipes (`touch-action: pan-y`). The tab bar full-bleeds to
  the viewport edges (`margin-inline: calc(var(--content-pad) * -1)`) with a
  full-width bottom border.

Rule of thumb: **content scrolls inside the card only on desktop**. On
tablet/mobile the card grows to its content and the surrounding region scrolls.

## Responsive breakpoints (reference)

- `< 768px` — mobile
- `768px` — tablet layout begins
- `1024px` — desktop **card** dashboard (3-col, internal scroll)
- `1200px` — desktop **header** single bar (independent of the card breakpoint)
